olcombe, Dorsetshire, England":"Woolcombe, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Meriden, Warwickshire, England":"Meriden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woolcombe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Woolacombe in Morthoe (Devon)."],"variants":[{"name":"Woolcomb","meanings":["English:  see  Woolcombe  ."]},{"name":"Walkham","meanings":["English:  see  Woolcombe  ."]},{"name":"Walkom","meanings":["English:  see  Woolcombe  ."]},{"name":"Walkem","meanings":["English:  see  Woolcombe  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan of Woolcombe was born in 1239, in Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir John Mautravers in 1260, in England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1297, in Meriden, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1239–1297":"1239–1297","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","1264–1330":"1264–1330","1266–1341":"1266–1341","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1292–1321":"1292–1321","about 1292":"umbes 1292","1264":"1264","1297":"1297","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1239":"1239","Abt 1262":"umbes 1262","1238":"1238","1268":"1268","1266":"1266","1321":"1321","about 1268":"umbes 1268","Lytchett Matravers, Dorset, England":"Lytchett Matravers, Dorset, England","Woolcombe, Dorset, England":"Woolcombe, Dorset, England","Lychet Maltravers, Dorset, England":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Wormleighton, Warwickshire, England":"Wormleighton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Woolcombe, Dorsetshire, England":"Woolcombe, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of  Woolcombe, Dorsetshire, England":"Woolcombe, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Meriden, Warwickshire, England":"Meriden, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1239–1297":"1239–1297","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","1264–1330":"1264–1